   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Very briefly, this shows the same aggregation pattern as eigenvector centrality but with a different message. Instead of sending scalar importance scores, nodes send probability mass. After enough updates, the mass concentrates on nodes that are easier to revisit in the walk. On this graph, the hub and bridge nodes attract more probability than the outer nodes because they lie on more walk routes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 2.4 Aggregation in the DeepWalk Algorithm\n",
    "\n",
    "Very briefly, this is the DeepWalk version of aggregation. Node 10 tends to co-occur most often with nodes that are structurally close to it in many sampled walks, especially its bridge neighbors. That is a **local** notion of aggregation because the window only looks a few steps to the left and right in a walk.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the key shift from random walk centrality to DeepWalk:\n",
    "- random walk centrality aggregates probability flow over the graph,\n",
    "- DeepWalk aggregates local co-occurrence patterns from many sampled walks,\n",
    "- Skip-gram then turns those co-occurrence patterns into an embedding."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In DeepWalk, the message is not a centrality score and not a probability mass. The message is **co-occurrence in a random-walk context window**. The algorithm samples many short random walks, treats each walk like a sentence, and then aggregates which nodes tend to appear near each other within a fixed window.\n",
    "\n",
    "So the aggregation pattern is:\n",
    "- sample random walks,\n",
    "- slide a local window along each walk,\n",
    "- count which nodes co-occur in those local contexts,\n",
    "- learn an embedding from those repeated local co-occurrence patterns."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
